# Daily Challenge:-20/02/2022.
**Approach:-** This is very simple Brute force approach.
Because the constrains are very Less that's why brute force works.

**What I'm Doing:-**
*Itrate from 0 to length of given interval array.*
-->For every ith Interval we check ,how many interval it is covering.
-->If any jth interval is covered by any ith interval,then we are doing two things.
    -->increment the count of covered interval.
   **-->To mark it covered ,we change its 1st value of covered interval(i.e jth) to -1.
   -->And during next itration we skip those intervals,which are already covered by some other intervals.**

-->At the end the variable count will indicate how many intervals we have covered.
-->So left uncovered interval are n-count. So return n-count.


**Time Complexity= O(n^2);
Auxiliary Space= O(1);**

Note:-Approach By Sorting is Another  Optimized Approach, But I'm Not Covering it here.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int removeCoveredIntervals(vector<vector<int>>& intervals) {
       int count=0; 
        int n=intervals.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) 
        {
            if(intervals[i][0]==-1) //If that Interval is Already Covered,Skip that.
                continue;

            for(int j=0;j<n;j++)
            {
                if(i==j||intervals[j][0]==-1) //i==j means same interval and intervals[j][0]==-1 means already covered.
                    continue;
                else if((intervals[i][0]<=intervals[j][0])&&(intervals[j][1]<=intervals[i][1]))
                {
                    /*Otherwise if jth interval is covered by ith.
                    Mark jth as Covered by Changing it's first value to -1;
                    And Increment the Count of Covered Interval.*/
                    intervals[j][0]=-1;
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }

        int left_uncovered=n-count; //Left uncovered Intervals.
        return left_uncovered; //return it.
    }
};
```
