If we simply apply ``` sort(intervals.begin(), intervals.end()) ``` then output will be ``` [[1,2],[1,4],[3,4]] ```. 

In this case covering interval [1,4] is coming after the covered interval [1,2].

Hence we have to modify the sorting in such a way that whenever two intervals have same start, the interval having higher end value should come first. Following function is used for the same.

```
bool static compare( const vector<int>& v1, const vector<int>& v2 ) 
    {
        if(v1[0]==v2[0])
            return v1[1]>v2[1];
        else
            return v1[0] < v2[0];
    }
```	
