Idea is say we have the test case : [[3,10],[4,10],[5,14],[5,11],[5,12]]
Post sorting : 3,10 / 4,10 / 5,14 / 5,12 / 5,11
According to this fitst our higher limit is 10. and the upper limit is already sorted in ascending order.
therfore 4,10 is always in range of 3,10 hence not incremented. (In genenal all ranges which have upper limit less 10 lie btw 3,10)
the next higher range is 14 .... all the numbers after it have higher ranges less than 14... hence the answer returned will be 2.
This could be flawed only if a test case such as 15,14 would exist. but the testcases are such lower range has to be less than the upper range.
```
class Solution {
    public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {

		//If the lower limit are not same it is sorted in descending. if the lower limit is same then in ascending.
        Arrays.sort(intervals,(a,b) -> a[0]==b[0] ? b[1] - a[1] : a[0] - b[0]);
        // for(int i=0;i<intervals.length;i++)
        //     System.out.println(intervals[i][0]+" "+intervals[i][1]);

        int count = 0;
        int higher = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        for(int i=0;i<intervals.length;i++)
        {

            if(intervals[i][1]>higher)
            {
                count++;
                higher = intervals[i][1];
                // System.out.println(count+" "+intervals[i][0]+" "+higher)//
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}

```

