# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Considering every column of top row as starting point. Then calculating minimum for every starting point till the end.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Consider every column of top row as starting point. Call recursion for those points, if index goes out of range return maximum and for bottom index return the matrix value. Go to every column of the adjacent row (except the column right below it,) using a loop. Take the minimum, update it & return it. Voila!

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int solve(int row, int col, vector<vector<int>> &nums,vector<vector<int>> &dp)
    {
        if(col<0 || col>nums[0].size()-1) return 1e9; // for out of index
        if(row==nums.size()-1) return nums[row][col];// when reached the bottom
        if(dp[row][col] != -1) return dp[row][col]; // return already calculated
        int ans=INT_MAX;
        for(int k=0;k<nums.size();k++){ // check for every column except just below one
            if(k!=col)
                ans=min(ans,nums[row][col]+solve(row+1,k,nums,dp)); // take minimum
        }
        return dp[row][col] = ans; // return answer
    }
    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& nums) {
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        int n = nums.size();
        int m = nums[0].size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n,vector<int>(m,-1));
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++) // considering every column of top row as starting point
            ans = min(ans,solve(0,i,nums,dp));//taking minimum for every starting point
        return ans;
    }
};
```

