solutions.content:
# Intuition
Question is similar to minimum falling path sum with a difference in direction. Here we the direction to move ahead from current position (row, col) will be (row+1, c); c will range from 0 to n leaving the previous column value col.
Here we have a variable starting and ending point so we can start from any cell in 0th row and end at any cell in n-1th row. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
## Recursion:
1. Express in indexes. We need i for row and j for column traversal.
2. We explore all the possibilities.
3. Figure out the minimum.

Say we have m cols and we start from n-1th row and move upwards.

```
for(int j=0; j < n; j++) {
    // Try every start position possibility
    // Minimum of all the possibilities is our answer.
    mini = min(mini, solve(n-1, j, grid));
}
```
solve(i, j) -> minimum path sum to react i, j from any cell in n-1th

Base Case:

1. if we reach the destination if(i==0)
2. out of bounds check if(j<0 or j>=m)

Check code below.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1. Recursion: For every cell we are exploring n paths and we are moving up to n rows: O(n^n)
2. Memoization: O(n*n) -> for every row n possibilities
3. Tabulation: O(N*N) 

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1. Recursion: O(n) ->stack space
2. Memoization: O(n*n) -> for dp array + O(n) ->stack space
3. Tabulation: to eliminate stack space -> O(n*n) ->for dp array
4. Space Optimization: O(n)

# Code
1. Recursion
```
class Solution {
public:
    int solve(int i, int j, vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        // Base condition if we reach teh destination
        if(i == 0) return grid[i][j];

        // Out of bounds check: We return a huge value so that the path is never taken.
        if(i<0 or j < 0 or j >= n) return 1e8;

        int mini = 1e8;

        for(int k =0; k<n; k++) {
            // such that no two elements chosen in adjacent rows are in the same column.
            if(k!=j) {
                // Minimum of all possibilities
                mini = min(mini, grid[i][j] + solve(i-1, k, grid));
            }
        }

        return mini;
    }

    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        int mini = 1e9;

        for(int j=0; j < n; j++) {
            // Try every start position possibility
            // Minimum of all the possibilities is our answer.
            mini = min(mini, solve(n-1, j, grid));
        }
    }
};
```
2. Memoization
```
class Solution {
public:
    int solve(int i, int j, vector<vector<int>>& grid, vector<vector<int>> &dp) {
        int n = grid.size();

        if(i == 0) return grid[i][j];

        if(i<0 or j < 0 or j >= n) return 1e8;

        if(dp[i][j] != -1000) return dp[i][j];

        int mini = 1e8;

        for(int k =0; k<n; k++) {
            if(k!=j) {
                mini = min(mini, grid[i][j] + solve(i-1, k, grid, dp));
            }
        }

        return dp[i][j] = mini;
    }
    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        int mini = 1e9;
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int> (n+1, -1000));
        for(int j=0; j < n; j++) {
            mini = min(mini, solve(n-1, j, grid, dp));
        }

        return mini;
    }
};
```
3. Tabulation
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        int mini = 1e9;

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1, vector<int> (n+1, 0));

        // To satisfy base condition
        for(int j=0; j<n; j++) dp[0][j] = grid[0][j];

        for(int i = 1; i<n; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++) {
                int mini = 1e8;

                for(int k =0; k<n; k++) {
                    if(k!=j) {
                        mini = min(mini, grid[i][j] + dp[i-1][k]);
                    }
                }

                dp[i][j] = mini;
            }
        }

        for(int j=0; j < n; j++) {
            mini = min(mini, dp[n-1][j]);
        }

        return mini;
    }
};
```
4. Space Optimization
We can optimize the 2D array space to 1-D array as for calculation we require only the previous row not the entire dp matrix
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
