solutions.content:
Before we go ahead, this method doesn't need to define a separate dp matrix, and is based heavily on the usage of min_element() command of c++.
For every row, if we have the min falling path sums of the matrix up till the previous row at every index, we need to find a way to update the min falling path sum at each of the index in our current row. 
Note that, you are always going to add the minimum falling path sum of the last row, unless the minimum value is in the same column as your index. 
In that case, you will go for the second smallest min falling sum of the above row. So, if we have the 2 smallest min falling path sum of each row, we can always find the min Falling Path Sum of the matrix. 

For ease of explanation and to keep it beginner-friendly I have coded the approach in the original matrix itself, however you can do the same by just keeping 1 vector that represents the current row and the two smallest min falling path sums of the previous row. This will give us a *O(N)* space DP method. 

Here's the easier version of the code, let me know if you have any doubts :)

```class Solution {
public:
    int minFallingPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        //find the two minimum elements of each row -> always one of two will be used
        int n =  grid.size(), m = grid[0].size();


        int min1, min2;
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++)
        {
            auto it = min_element(grid[i-1].begin(), grid[i-1].end());
            int temp = *it;
            min1 = it - grid[i-1].begin();
             *it = INT_MAX;
            auto it2 = min_element(grid[i-1].begin(), grid[i-1].end());
            min2 = it2 - grid[i-1].begin();
            *it = temp;

            for(int j = 0; j < m; j++)
            {
                if(j == min1)
                {
                    grid[i][j] += grid[i-1][min2];
                }
                else{
                    grid[i][j] += grid[i-1][min1];
                }
            }
        }

        return *min_element(grid[n-1].begin(), grid[n-1].end());
    }
};
```

