**Solution#1:** Time Complexity: `O(m*n)` Space Complexity: `O(m*n)` 
**Idea:**
* let's maintain a 2d matrix `dp[][]` where `dp[i][j]` would be the falling path sum ending at `arr[i][j]` (this may not be minimum)
* We need the minimum value of the last row of the dp and return it as answer
* In order to maintain `dp[i][j]`, we need the minimum path sum on the row above, and left, and row above on the right. Whichever is minimum, we will carry forward to `dp[i][j]`.
* So, the optimal substructure is:
	* `dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][0..j-1], dp[i-1][j+1..cols-1]) + arr[i][j]`
	* consider the boundary elements appropriately when coding
* In the end, iterate over the last row of the dp, and determine the answer. (You can maintain the answer while determining `dp[i][j]` as well with few tweaks)

```
public int minFallingPathSum(int[][] arr) {
	int rows = arr.length,
		cols = arr[0].length,
		ans = arr[0][0];

	int[][] dp = new int[rows][cols];
	dp[0] = arr[0];

	int[] minTill = new int[cols],
		minFrom = new int[cols];

	minTill[0] = arr[0][0];
	for (int j = 1; j < cols; j++) {
		minTill[j] = Math.min(minTill[j-1], arr[0][j]);
	}

	minFrom[cols-1] = arr[0][cols-1];
	for (int j = cols-2; j >= 0; j--) {
		minFrom[j] = Math.min(minFrom[j+1], arr[0][j]);
	}

	for (int i = 1; i < rows; i++) {
		int[] nextMinTill = new int[cols];
		int ansCand = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
		// System.out.println("minTill: " + Arrays.toString(minTill));
		for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
			int cand1 = (j > 0)
					? minTill[j-1]
					: Integer.MAX_VALUE,
				cand2 = j < cols-1
					? minFrom[j+1]
					: Integer.MAX_VALUE;

			dp[i][j] = Math.min(cand1, cand2) + arr[i][j];
			ansCand = Math.min(ansCand, dp[i][j]);

			nextMinTill[j] = (j == 0)
				? dp[i][j]
				: Math.min(nextMinTill[j-1], dp[i][j]);
		}

		// update minFrom
		minFrom[cols-1] = dp[i][cols-1];
		for (int j = cols-2; j >= 0; j--) {
			minFrom[j] = Math.min(dp[i][j], minFrom[j+1]);
		}

		minTill = nextMinTill;
		ans = ansCand;
	}
	return ans;
```

**Solution#2:** Time Complexity: `O(m*n)` Space Complexity: `O(n)` 
* If you see carefully to the optimal substructure mentioned above, we decide the value of `dp[i][j]` based only upon the previous row of the 2d matrix `dp`.
* This means, we don't need to maintinain the entire 2d matrix `dp`, we can only maintain current and previous row of the dp, keeping the rest of the things same.

```
public int minFallingPathSum(int[][] arr) {
	int rows = arr.length,
		cols = arr[0].length,
		ans = arr[0][0];

	int[][] dp = new int[2][cols];
	dp[0] = arr[0];

	int[] minTill = new int[cols],
		minFrom = new int[cols];

	minTill[0] = arr[0][0];
	for (int j = 1; j < cols; j++) {
		minTill[j] = Math.min(minTill[j-1], arr[0][j]);
	}

	minFrom[cols-1] = arr[0][cols-1];
	for (int j = cols-2; j >= 0; j--) {
		minFrom[j] = Math.min(minFrom[j+1], arr[0][j]);
	}

	for (int i = 1; i < rows; i++) {
		int[] nextMinTill = new int[cols];
		int ansCand = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
		// System.out.println("minTill: " + Arrays.toString(minTill));
		for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
			int cand1 = (j > 0)
					? minTill[j-1]
					: Integer.MAX_VALUE,
				cand2 = j < cols-1
					? minFrom[j+1]
					: Integer.MAX_VALUE;

			dp[1][j] = Math.min(cand1, cand2) + arr[i][j];
			ansCand = Math.min(ansCand, dp[1][j]);

			dp[0] = dp[1];
		}

		// update minTill
		minTill[0] = dp[0][0];
		for (int j = 1; j < cols; j++) {
			minTill[j] = Math.min(minTill[j-1], dp[0][j]);
		}

		// update minFrom
		minFrom[cols-1] = dp[0][cols-1];
		for (int j = cols-2; j >= 0; j--) {
			minFrom[j] = Math.min(dp[0][j], minFrom[j+1]);
		}

		ans = ansCand;
	}
	return ans;
}
```

**Solution#3:** Time Complexity: `O(m*n)` Space Complexity: `O(1)` 
* If you understand the problem carefully, all we need is, minimum value in each row.
* If the minimum value in current row is at the same column position as previous, than we need to consider the second minimum value in previous calculation. We also need to keep track of `prevPos` for this purpose.

```
public int minFallingPathSum(int[][] arr) {
	int rows = arr.length,
		cols = arr[0].length,
		prevPos = -1,
		prevFirstMin = 0,
		prevSecondMin = 0;

	for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
		int nextFirstMin = Integer.MAX_VALUE,
			nextSecondMin = Integer.MAX_VALUE,
			nextPos = -1;

		for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
			int cur = arr[i][j] + (j == prevPos
									? prevSecondMin
									: prevFirstMin);

			if (cur < nextFirstMin) {
				nextPos = j;
				nextSecondMin = nextFirstMin;
				nextFirstMin = cur;

			} else if (cur < nextSecondMin) {
				nextSecondMin = cur;

			}
		}

		prevFirstMin = nextFirstMin;
		prevSecondMin = nextSecondMin;
		prevPos = nextPos;
	}

	return prevFirstMin;
}
```

