*From Geeksforgeeks:*
The << (left shift) in C or C++ takes two numbers, left shifts the bits of the first operand, the second operand decides the number of places to shift.

For example, if we have an int and it is initalized to 4, it looks like this in binary
000.........0000000100

If we do a left shift of 1, it'll look like this
000.........0000001000 
giving us a value of 8. 

So we initalize a variable to be 0 so all the bits are set to 0. 
Then when we loop through linked list, we bitshift by 1. 
From there we either add 0 or 1 to the binary value. 

By doing this, we can work backwards. 
If our length of the list is 3, 
we needed to calculate 2^2 + 2^1 + 2^0 . By bitshifting left, we can start from 2^2.

