solutions.content:
One can note that the next sequential number of the same length can be obtained by adding a sequence of ```1```s to the previous number:
```
23 = 12 + 11
34 = 23 + 11
45678 = 34567 + 11111
```

And another fun fact is that the smallest sequential number of the next length can also be obtained by adding a sequence of ```1```s:
```
123 = 12 + 111
1234 = 123 + 1111
12345 = 1234 + 11111
```

So, the task can be solved in two nested loops:
- the outer loop will iterate through the length of the number, producing the smallest sequential number of the given length (12, 123, 1234, 12345, ...)
- the inner loop will iterate through all sequential numbers of the given length by adding ```1```s to the smallest candidate.
This way the candidates are already generated in ascending order, so no explicit sorting is required.

```
class Solution
{
public:
    vector<int> sequentialDigits(int low, int high)
    {
        vector<int>     result;
        int     cand = 1;
        int     diff = 1;
        for (int len = 2; len < 10; ++len)
        {
            diff = diff*10 + 1;      // It will be: 11, then 111, then 1111, ...
            cand += diff;            // It will be: 12, then 123, then 1234, ...
        //  The line above can also be: "cand = cand*10 + len;"
            int probe = cand;
            for (int rest = len; rest < 10; ++rest, probe += diff)
            {
                if ((probe >= low) && (probe <= high))
                    result.push_back(probe);
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

